04726nam a22007335i 9781787440685DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874406857 a10.1515/97817874406852doi  a(DE-B1597)675132  a(OCoLC)1420507069  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a821/.109qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aBiggs, Frederick M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChaucer's Decameron and the Origin of the ‹I›Canterbury Tales‹/I› /cFrederick M. Biggs.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2017] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (292 p.) :b7 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChaucer Studies ;v4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tConventions for Citing Editions -- tIntroduction -- t1 Boccaccio as the Source for Chaucer’s Use of Sources -- t2 The Shipman’s Trade in Three Novelle from the Decameron -- t3 Licisca’s Outburst: The Origin of the Canterbury Tales -- t4 Friar Puccio’s Penance: Upending the Knight’s Order -- t5 The Wife of Bath’s Tale and the Tale of Florent -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Passages from the works of Boccaccio, Chaucer, and Gower, and from Heile van Beersele -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA major and original contribution to the debate as to Chaucer's use and knowledge of Boccaccio, finding a new source for the "Shipman's Tale".A possible direct link between the two greatest literary collections of the fourteenth century, Boccaccio's Decameron and Chaucer's Canterbury Tales, has long tantalized readers because these works share many stories, which are, moreover, placed in similar frames. And yet, although he identified many of his sources, Chaucer never mentioned Boccaccio; indeed when he retold the Decameron's final novella, his pilgrim, the Clerk, states that it was written by Petrarch. For these reasons, most scholars now believe that while Chaucer might have heard parts of the earlier collection when he was in Italy, he did not have it at hand as he wrote. This volumeaims to change our understanding of this question. It analyses the relationship between the "Shipman's Tale", originally written for the Wife of Bath, and Decameron 8.10, not seen before as a possible source. The book alsoargues that more important than the narratives that Chaucer borrowed is the literary technique that he learned from Boccaccio - to make tales from ideas. This technique, moreover, links the "Shipman's Tale" to the "Miller's Tale"and the new "Wife of Bath's Tale". Although at its core a hermeneutic argument, this book also delves into such important areas as alchemy, domestic space, economic history, folklore, Irish/English politics, manuscripts, and misogyny. FREDERICK M. BIGGS is Professor of English at the University of Connecticut.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBoccaccio.  aargument.  aart history.  aarthurian.  aauthors.  acanterbury tales.  achaucer.  adebate.  adecameron.  aevidence.  afourteenth century.  ahistory.  aliterary.  aliterature.  amedieval.  amiddle ages.  apoet.  apoetry.  awriting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178744068540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440685/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles